Environmental Social Categorization Rati:
This is a Category B project according to IFC's Procedure for Environmental and Social Review of Projects because a limited number of specific environmental and social impacts may result, which can be avoided or mitigated by adhering to generally recognized performance standards, guidelines or design criteria. Key environmental, health and safety, human resources and social issues that were reviewed included the following:

- Environmental and social management system;
- Quality and sustainability of water resources;
- Emissions to the environment  air, water and subsurface; 
- Solid and hazardous materials management, including transportation, handling and storage;
- Life and fire safety; 
- Community and occupational health and safety; 
- Traffic safety
- Energy use and efficiency; and 
- Community engagement. 

The company has presented specific plans to address key issues and gaps to ensure compliance with local regulatory requirements as well as consistency with IFC Performance Standards and applicable sections of the World Bank Group (WBG) Environmental, Health and Safety guidelines, during the construction phase and when the plant is operational. Additionally, new technology, energy efficiency and recovery provide a significant positive impact on global climate change. The project will create additional employment opportunities for local communities. Environmental and Social Impact Assessments (ESIA) are currently underway which included consultation with the local community on potential project related impacts. On completion, the ESIA will be disclosed publicly and require approval by the local government prior to commencement of activities for which an approved ESIA is required.

Impact:
The project is expected to have the following development impacts: 
Provision of Business Infrastructure Services: The project will add 29,383 square meters of quality real estate infrastructure to Kigali and support the implementation of the Kigali City Master Plan;
Employment: The project will create a minimum of 100 jobs during construction and further 15-20 jobs post construction. The project will also create indirect jobs through supply chains;
Demonstration Effect: IFC's involvement in the project will act as a catalyst to encourage other financial institutions to partner with strong and reputable local sponsors on similar projects in the country;
Energy Efficiency: The property design includes energy efficient components like solar powered extractor fans, heat reflective glass etc that when implemented will have a demonstration effect as one of the few true energy efficient buildings in Kigali.

1. IFC's strategy includes a focus on under-served markets, such as Tripoli which is Lebanon's 2nd largest city and is based in a 'Frontier Region'. This will be IFC's first investment outside of Beirut, and will contribute to more balanced regional growth, which is essential to support greater social cohesion; 

2. Support development of high value addition in the ICT sector in Lebanon: figures released by the United Nations Conference on Trade and Development ('UNCTAD') indicate that Lebanon is one of the largest exporters of Information and Technology ('IT') services among the middle East and North Africa ('MENA') region. Supporting companies like MobiNetS help demonstrate Lebanon's ability to produce world class ICT services;

3. Increase employment opportunities through companies like MobiNetS, which benefit local ICT professionals by creating high quality job opportunities and developing skills in the value-added ICT services sector. This investment can also help these businesses retain talent within Lebanon, increasing the country's chances of further economic prosperity; and

4. Support cost effective infrastructure services:  investing in a company like MobiNetS which contributes to reduce inefficiencies and generates cost savings, is fully in line with the World Bank Group's strategy in the ICT sector.

